{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491326"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:43:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:43:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"914"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/914"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.51,0.34,0.03,0.1,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"914"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77647"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/914"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"914"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63160"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"834"},{"type":"contributions","id":"919"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1543"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26675"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77647"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for review. Three months ago, she sustained a fractured femur requiring open reduction and internal fixation. Her post-operative course was complicated by a segmental pulmonary embolus, for which she was commenced on apixaban. She has no significant medical history and takes no other regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She reports no respiratory symptoms, and her leg shows no swelling or functional impairment.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management of her anticoagulation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cease apixaban","Continue apixaban for three months","Continue apixaban indefinitely","Change to warfarin","Change to rivaroxaban"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a provoked venous thromboembolism (VTE) following orthopaedic surgery, which is a significant but temporary risk factor. The management approach depends on whether the VTE was provoked or unprovoked, and whether risk factors persist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECease apixaban\u003C/strong\u003E is appropriate as she has completed three months of anticoagulation for a provoked VTE where the provoking factor (surgery) is no longer present. The risk of recurrence is low once the initial three-month treatment period is complete.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue apixaban for three months\u003C/strong\u003E would mean six months total therapy, which is unnecessary for a provoked VTE with resolved risk factors. Extended anticoagulation increases bleeding risk without providing additional benefit in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue apixaban indefinitely\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for unprovoked VTE, recurrent VTE, or ongoing risk factors such as active cancer. None of these factors are present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChange to warfarin\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as changing anticoagulants during the treatment period increases the risk of both bleeding and recurrent thrombosis. Additionally, warfarin requires regular INR monitoring and is generally reserved for specific situations such as severe renal impairment or antiphospholipid syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChange to rivaroxaban\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as there is no advantage to changing between direct oral anticoagulants, and doing so may increase complications. If a direct oral anticoagulant is working well, it should be continued for the duration of therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anticoagulation for a provoked venous thromboembolism should be ceased after three months if the provoking factor is no longer present.","Surgery and trauma are significant provoking factors for venous thromboembolism that do not require extended anticoagulation once resolved.","The choice of anticoagulant should not be changed during the treatment period due to increased risks of bleeding and recurrence."],"references":["Tran HA, Gibbs H, Merriman E, Curnow JL, Young L, Bennett A, et al. New guidelines from the Thrombosis and Haemostasis Society of Australia and New Zealand for the diagnosis and management of venous thromboembolism. The Medical Journal of Australia. 2019/02/11;210(5).","Choosing wisely [Internet]. [cited 2025 Jan 07]. Recommendations from the Haematology Society of Australia and New Zealand. Available from: https://www.choosingwisely.org.au/recommendations/hsanz3"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63160"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"914"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63160"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T20:59:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T21:01:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"914"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77647"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"positio